The user updates his self-description as follows: I now prefer jangly, guitar‑forward vintage mono recordings with live‑in‑studio immediacy: concise 2–4‑minute songs, punchy preserved transients, close upfront harmonies, clear instrument separation, and cohesive LP sequencing. I like minimal remastering that keeps tasteful analog grit so long as lead vocals and rhythmic bite stay immediate.
From past tastes I still prioritize intimate, front‑and‑center lead vocals, strong lyric‑forward hooks and sing‑along choruses, preserved dynamics, wide instrument separation that reveals arrangement detail, and occasional clean three‑ or four‑part harmonies.
Dislikes: warm, mid‑focused saturation or tonal matching that thickens or buries the lead vocal; extended album versions and long solos that dilute concise pop hooks; heavy compression or mastering that flattens transients; inconsistent mastering, dense synth‑or rhythm‑first mixes, or production choices that sacrifice vocal immediacy.

